Whether in a Lada or Bajaj as my aunt suggests, the default method in India is for open backs on three wheeled autos, although in Turkey it’s the Toyota Corolla that routinely turns up to tomorrowland. I don’t know if the proverbial Postman Pajero patronizes Beijing most, but the tradition seems widespread. In Turkey, you’ll be let out on the road doubling as a sidewalk. In Kazakhstan, a busy pedestrian side-walk will escort you past the fruit market until you’re certain you could not have been sleeping as its 8pm.

Thus, when confronted with symptoms like those produced in America by Prozac, Europe by alcohol or Mexico by coffee and cigarettes (as observed from the American border), anywhere in Turkey, Kazakhstan, India or Indonesia a quick exit into an unrelated, perambulatory, conversation naturally presents itself along with a bottle of locally produced fruit juice, hot ginger tea or mango milkshake. Could all this be new to you? To be honest, given you have adolescent wanderlust I’d imagine the answer is probably yes.
